“Tout ce que j’ai fait après mon accident et avec mon handicap est pour moi la preuve que je peux accomplir tout ce que je veux.”

Malgré un accident de voiture qui a bouleversé sa vie en la laissant en fauteuil avec une jambe en moins, Marcela Marañon (@thejourneyofabravewoman ) a démontré une incroyable force de caractère. Ski, ski nautique, randonnée ou encore ascension du Kilimanjaro, elle a dépassé les limites et prouvé que rien n’est impossible ! 💪
En plus de ses exploits sportifs, Marcela milite également pour une meilleure accessibilité des espaces publics et pour un changement de regard sur les personnes handicapées. 👩‍🦽

For those of you who want to know how I drive it with lower limb paralysis. This is not electric. It uses fuel. They built a nice rack for the chair. I have to build a new rack for my new wheelchair. I can add a second seat if I want but I will not be able to take the wheelchair with me. 

Video is old and I hope it answers your questions 🫶🏼

Many of the children and their parents are excluded from village communities due to their disability. There is a high level of communal stigmatization and many of those children are denied education and schooling. The children lack a place where they can grow up sheltered , loved and receive education.

We want to build a House of Hope, a center of Recovery, where kids and their parents can find necessary further treatment, education and shelter after their time spent in the hospital. Children should be able to grow up without beeing stigmatized and excluded. They should have the chance to thrive and grow and play, feeling unconditionally loved and accepted. Currently we have 80 kids in the program and the number keeps growing every year. If you would like to support by making a small donation, click the link in my bio or in the comment section. Anything amount helps. Thank you! 

This is the beginning and it will take a village! 🙏🏻 @haydom_friends

My power assist device has changed the way I travel. It makes every travel easy and fun! I have a @handsonconcepts wheelchair and both are very easy to assemble together. Airlines will ask if it has a lithium battery (yes, it has) and ask to take it with you. 

The nominal energy of the battery is 288 Wh which is below the IATA limit of 300 Wh (per battery). This is not new “information” before we travel we must call the airlines to let them know about our medical devices. Don’t forget! 

@unawheel.eu UNAwheel Maxi model and it comes with a certified letter showing the device is safe to fly with. 

#powerassist #wheelchairlife #wheelchairlifestyle #reel #reeloftheday #instagood #inclusionmatters #motivation #inspiration #travel #travelingtheworld #igers

Istanbul is one of the most beautiful cities I have visited! If you want to know about wheelchair access, I can tell you now that you will struggle, especially if you stay in the old city. Take a power assist device with you. Istanbul is very hilly but beautiful. You will LOVE it! I traveled alone and hired a tour guide to drive me around. The Golden Horn is considered to be the world’s largest natural harbor and you can take the cruise on Bosphorus (my favorite place in Istanbul)

It’s been 21 years since my car accident, and I firmly believe that the most precious thing in this life is good health. With good health, you can achieve your dreams. As you may know, last year, I fell seriously ill and came close to losing my other leg. It was a tough year of recovery, and I’m still on the journey to healing. During my time in the hospital, undergoing two hours of hyperbaric oxygen therapy every day, 3 months of IV antibiotics, I prayed to God for the gift of health so that I could once again savor the simple joys of life. After this profound experience, all I desire is health, not just for myself but for my loved ones as well, because we cannot thrive on superficial things. Our true wealth lies in health and love.

A reminder to all the women living with SCI, who are out there thriving and facing health challenges as well: This life isn’t easy, but we must always prioritize our health and listen to our bodies when they don’t feel right. If you think my life is perfect, it’s not. I also have struggles.

Here are photos I took during those 21 years.

I attended the @wandercraft.official personal exoskeleton keynote in NYC yesterday, where I met Kevin and the lovely Charlotte from France. 🇫🇷❤️ Both have been wheelchair users for years and have recently benefited from Wandercraft’s exoskeleton technology.

The personal exoskeleton, the first self-balanced of its kind, eliminates the need for crutches. Operated by a stick remote control, it boasts numerous cool features such as leaning over to pick up items from the floor, climbing stairs up and down, and a dynamic active balance mode. The personal exoskeleton will soon be available for testing in NYC.

For any questions about the Personal exoskeleton reach out to them directly. 

@charlotte_fairbank @noxton78

Today, as I turn another year older, I won’t make a cheesy post. I’m the most loud, energetic, adventurous, strong-headed woman you’ll ever meet, but behind that strong personality hides determination to finish things and make them happen.

I embarked on my journey with exoskeleton technology a decade ago, aspiring to witness fellow individuals with spinal cord injuries benefit from walking assistance. Having spent 21 years in a wheelchair, I’ve successfully adapted to life, embracing normalcy with my disability. For eight years, I walked with ReWalk until it became non-functional. This year, post a foot injury, I experienced the joy of walking with Atalante a few times. It’s bittersweet, but witnessing others walk with exoskeleton technology fills me with genuine happiness. Advocating for this cause almost a decade ago, I’m a living proof of how this technology can positively impact our health. The continuous improvement and increased accessibility of this technology fill me with excitement and hope.

I love witnessing others embrace this technology, seeing them in the spotlight and hearing stories of their improved health. Even if they’re not walking unassisted, the secondary health issues of living with SCI don’t steal their joy and vitality. It makes me truly emotional and feel that my advocacy hasn’t been in vain and it’s their time to shine and lead the way for others. ✨ 

2024 is going to be a year full of good news and I cannot wait for this technology to keep getting better.
Wishing you a year ahead filled with joy, new beginnings, and the delightful journey of turning dreams into reality. Happy New Year! 🎆 🫶🏼
